  <marc:subfield code="a">This is a manuscript of piyutim for the circumcision ceremony which was created for the purpose of accompanying the ceremony, through the blessings and the circumcision up until the final meal celebrations. The instructions for the ceremony and recitation of the piyutim are written in Italian cursive script in between the lines of the liturgy, written in Italian square script with vocalization. Local customs include the recitation of Psalms 65:10 between the first and second blessings of the circumcision and before the blessing of Sheheh&#x323;iyanu (f. 18v); the reason is stated that the verse contains ten words, and is momentous for the ten canopies which will be provided for the righteous in the world to come; notably, R. Moses Isserles notes this minhag and that it comes from the Zohar, but could not locate those who practiced it (see, ibid., Darke Mosheh to T&#x323;ur Yoreh De&#x2BB;ah 265:4). While this practice is novel to the community of this manuscript, there is no mention of the father of the child reciting the first blessing, which may be inferred from the instruction for the father of the child to recite the verse of the psalm, right below the blessing (see Shulh&#x323;an &#x2BB;arukh Yoreh de&#x2BB;ah 265:1). The manuscript finishes with two versions of the final verses and prayer at the ceremony itself (which includes the naming of the child) for when the father or &#x200F; e mother is not alive; this is written in unvocalized Italian cursive script (f. 21v). Decorated with a cherub face on the cartouche of the caption title (f. 1r); many cases of &#x5D9;&#x5D9;., the tetragrammaton abbreviated, come with a special ligature (for example, f. 9r). Bound in original brown gilt binding with floral patterns.</marc:subfield>
